What Spark actually is.

Apache Spark is a distributed compute engine. You write code as if you have one giant table. Behind the scenes, Spark slices that data into pieces called partitions. It assigns each partition to a machine, telling that machine exactly which file and which byte range to read. It runs your code on every partition in parallel, and then it brings the results back.

The mental shift from pandas is the important part. Pandas runs your code in one process, against memory it owns directly. Spark runs a plan that you describe, across many processes on many machines, and it moves data between them for you.

So you are no longer calling functions that execute immediately in local memory. You are describing work that Spark will schedule and distribute. That distinction — one process on owned memory, versus a distributed plan — is what every later idea in this course builds on.
